font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">public services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">to grassroots community groups, rather than to large</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">private or third sector organisations?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have not seen any clear evidence of local success, rather the reverse. For example th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e Councils of Bristol, North Somerset, South Gloucestershire and Bath and North East Somerset have awarded contracts to run local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Healthwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to a third sector organisation which has a history of winning contracts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with them. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is no publicly available </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">information </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to explain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">governance arrangements for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Heal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thwat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, including arrangements for </span><sp