rvice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">provision or should we be looking instead at greater control by users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">so they can ensure that public services become more responsive to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">changing needs?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If users see evidence that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">providers of public services are open and accountable, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> less likely they are to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demand more choice. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here is a long way to go before users have the control intended by Open Services White Paper. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How do we make</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> sure that all citizens are able to influence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </sp